Irrelevant info. Both parties already presented their results in 1940. Given the context of the Second Vienna Award, the important information was the population of North Transylvania during the Second Vienna Award, meaning in 1940, not one year later following known migration of Hungarians inside North Transylvania and Romanains outside North Transylvania. It's dishonest, like presenting Karellia's population in Finland 1 year after USSR annexed it and many Finns left and many Russians came in.

I simply do not find it accurate to use the 1941 census to represent the state of Northern Transylvania in 1940. Especially when we have both Romanian & Hungarian estimations, so any bias can be ruled out. And when we know the reason for the vastly different numbers between 1940 - 1941.
Added explaination for the 1940 - 1941 differences, with info taken from these pages: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Second_Vienna_Award ; https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Northern_Transylvania
/* A lot of incorrect info added */ Reply

Disagree. There is a Hungarian estimation made in 1940. https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Second_Vienna_Award#Statistics The numbers changed from 37/38% to 53.5% Hungarians because of Romanian leaving North Transylvania and Hungarians migrating towards North Transylvania after the Second Vienna Award. The Hungarian census from 1941 is already present in the article, however the most relevant data is the population at the moment of the annexation, not 1 year after following population movement.
Please use the 1940 data rather than the 1941 data. As the annexation happened in 1940.

please, go on the talk-page, you have a very distorted version of the events. Please read Willson's points. One of the reason of the dismemberment of Austria-Hungary was one of his points. Points 10 & 11. Please stop inserting OR.

A lot of the content you removed was sourced content. A case could be made that this is not 'incorrect statement' but simply historians having different opinions over the same event. Let us talk on the talk page about this.

The national assemblies of 1918-1920 were not meant to upersede democratic full-scale plebiscites/referendums, they were meant to express the will of the minorities of Austria-Hungary to the Entente. It is already mentioned previously that the only plebiscite was held in Sopron.

The source in question mentions that approximation. As far as I know, there are no speculations radically different from this one on the population of Transylvania during WW1. If you have another source with radically different speculation a case could be made for lack of academic consensus. But as it stands right now, this speculation is very similar with the Austro-Hungarian census in 1910 and the Romanian census in 1919. With the other changes I agree.
